The term as used herein an "expression regulatory sequence" means a polynucleotide sequence required for the expression of a coding sequence and the implementation of processing which were connected with it.

        The suitable transcription|transfer start for an expression regulatory sequence, a conclusion, a promoter, and enhancer arrangement|sequence;

        RNA processing signal with the sufficient efficiency of splicing, the polyadenylation signal, etc.;

        Arrangement|sequence which stabilizes cytoplasm mRNA;

        Arrangement|sequence which improves translation efficiency (namely, Kozak consensus sequence);

        Arrangement|sequence which improves protein stability;

        And when desiring, there exists an arrangement|sequence which raises protein secretion.

        The properties of such a regulatory sequence differ according to a host organism;

        Generally in a prokaryote, such a regulatory sequence has a promoter, a ribosome binding site, and a transcription termination arrangement|sequence;

        Generally in an eukaryote, such a regulatory sequence has a promoter and a transcription termination arrangement|sequence.

        The term a "regulatory sequence" shall contain at a minimum all the structural components with the presence indispensable for an expression and processing.

        The further structural component that becomes advantageous by the presence, for example, a leader sequence, and a fusion partner arrangement|sequence can also be included.

"Conservative amino acid substitution" is substituted in this specification by the other amino acid residue in which an amino acid residue has the side chain R group to which chemical property (for example, an electric charge or hydrophobicity) was similar.

        Generally, in conservative amino acid substitution, a protein functional characteristic does not change substantially.

        When an at least two amino acid sequence mutually changes with conservative substitution, % sequence identity can be adjusted upwards and a substituted conservative property can be corrected.

        A means to perform this adjustment is known to an expert.

        For example, please refer Pearson, Methods Mol.Biol., 243:307-31(1994).

        In the example of the group of an amino acid which has the side chain to which chemical property was similar, they are 1 aliphatic-side-chain:glycine, alanine, valine, a leucine, and isoleucine;

        2) Aliphatic hydroxyl side chain : serine and threonine;

        3) Amide|amido containing side chain : asparagine and glutamine;

        4) Aromatic side chain : phenylalanine, tyrosine, and tryptophan;

        5) Basic side chain;

        A lysine|ricin, arginine, and histidine;

        6) Acidic side chain : aspartic acid and glutamic acid;

        and

        7) Sulfur containing side chain : there exist cysteine and methionine.

        For example, the groups of conservative amino acid substitution may be valine- leucine-isoleucine, phenylalanine tyrosine, leucine- arginine, alanine-valine-, glutamic acid-aspartic acid and asparagine- glutamine.

In this specification, "abnormal cell proliferation" refers to the cell growth (for example, loss of a contact inhibition) unrelated to a normal control system including the abnormal proliferation of healthy cells, and the proliferation of an abnormal cell, unless it shows specially.

        Although not restricted to this so,

        Abnormal proliferation of the tumor cells (tumor) propagated by the expression of tyrosine kinase or the overexpression of receptor tyrosine kinase which mutated;

        Abnormal proliferation of the beningnant and malignant cell of the other proliferative disease from which activation of abnormal tyrosine kinase arises;

        Abnormal proliferation of the arbitrary tumor propagated by receptor tyrosine kinase;

        Abnormal proliferation of the arbitrary tumor propagated by activation of abnormal serine / threonine kinase;

        Abnormal proliferation of the beningnant and malignant cell of the other proliferative disease from which activation of abnormal serine / threonine kinase arises;

        Abnormal proliferation of the tumor of both the benignancy in which the activation Ras oncogene is expressing, and malignancy;

        Abnormal proliferation of the tumor cells of both the benignancy by which Ras protein was activated as a result of the carcinogenic mutation in another gene, and malignancy;

        The abnormal proliferation of the beningnant and malignant cell of the other proliferation disease from which abnormal Ras activation arises is included.

        The examples of such a benign proliferative disease are psoriasis, a benign prostatic hypertrophy, a human papilloma virus (HPV), and restenosis.

        "Abnormal cell proliferation" also points out the abnormal proliferation of the cell of both the benignancy which arises from the activity of enzyme farnesyl protein transferase, and malignancy, and contains it.

